Description. Adult. In addition to characters listed in the diagnosis, palpus (
Fig. 13
) with 3 rd segment bearing shallow pit of diameter about ½ width of segment and containing few, elongate, capitate sensilla; wing ( Fig. 6, 7 ) relatively strongly patterned with about 1 / 5 of cell r 2 included in the post-stigmatic pale marking; legs (
Fig. 19
) pale brown, hind femora unbanded, mid and fore femora with subapical pale band, all tibiae with pale subbasal band, mid & hind tibia additionally with weak pale apical bands; haltere pale. Male hypopygium (Fig. 37 ) with ninth sternite with ventral membrane bare. Aedeagus (Fig. 39 ) with peg strongly sclerotised and quite dark.

Biology. Closely associated with bovids. Immatures live in discrete bovid dung pats (
Canon & Reye 1966
,
Campbell & Kettle 1976
) while adults feed on sheep, cattle, marsupial, buffalo, human and horse (Lee et al. 1962 ;
Kay 1973
;
Muller & Murray 1977
;
Muller et al. 1981
; Kay & Lennon 1982 ). Adults are crepuscular (
Campbell & Kettle 1979 b
;
Bellis et al. 2004
), roost in ground herbage during daylight hours (
Bishop et al. 1995
) and mate in swarms at sunset (
Campbell & Kettle 1979 a
). This species has been implicated in the transmission of 19 different viruses, including several of economic importance (
Doherty et al. 1972
, St
George et al. 1977
, 1978 , 1979 , 1983 ;
Muller et al. 1982
;
Zakrewski & Cybinski 1984
;
Parsonson & Snowdon 1985
;
Standfast et al. 1985
;
Cybinski & Muller 1990
).
